{"source_key":"sha256-55c0d933a7f998cb7adfcb0cf65f3444","record_index":270,"record_hash":"sha256:bd8af808d925cdb8146fbd2ecd86bc11ce0cbf0dbd96dea811ae2954f253f2cd","timestamp":"2026-05-20T15:19:04.456Z","kind":"message","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:message","role":"user","text":"<subagent_notification>\n{\"agent_path\":\"[REDACTED:entropy]\",\"status\":{\"completed\":\"**Findings**\\n\\n[P1] The environment pass makes the existing capture race much worse.  \\n[gitmeta.rs:103](/Users/kiril/src/gitbutler/crates/but-agentlog/src/gitmeta.rs:103) reads `previous_turn_key`, [gitmeta.rs:109](/Users/kiril/src/gitbutler/crates/but-agentlog/src/gitmeta.rs:109) reads/dedupes `record-hashes`, then [gitmeta.rs:169](/Users/kiril/src/gitbutler/crates/but-agentlog/src/gitmeta.rs:169) does workspace/worktree/commit diff collection before [gitmeta.rs:227](/Users/kiril/src/gitbutler/crates/but-agentlog/src/gitmeta.rs:227) writes. Two concurrent hook captures can both accept the same records, compute the same turn, append duplicate transcript/turn entries, or set the same `previous_turn_key`. This needs the spec’s lock/optimistic retry, or at minimum the expensive environment work must not sit inside the stale read-to-write window.\\n\\n[P1] Synthetic change ids are stored as real observed change facts.  \\n[environment.rs:270](/Users/kiril/src/gitbutler/crates/but-agentlog/src/environment.rs:270) calls `commit.change_id()`, which synthesizes a fallback when the commit has no stored change id, then [environment.rs:271](/Users/kiril/src/gitbutler/crates/but-agentlog/src/environment.rs:271) projects it into `observed_targets.changes`; [environment.rs:86](/Users/kiril/src/gitbutler/crates/but-agentlog/src/environment.rs:86) also makes `CommitSnapshot.change_id` mandatory. That conflicts with the Environment-pass contract’s “optional change id” and will later make change indexes claim evidence for ordinary Git commits that never had a GitButler change id. Use `commit.change_id.as_ref()` for persisted/projected change evidence.\\n\\n[P2] Path storage is lossy, so distinct repo facts can collapse.  \\n[environment.rs:333](/Users/kiril/src/gitbutler/crates/but-agentlog/src/environment.rs:333) extracts Git paths as bytes, but [environment.rs:357](/Users/kiril/src/gitbutler/crates/but-agentlog/src/environment.rs:357) stores them with `to_str_lossy()`. Non-UTF-8 paths can be corrupted or collide after replacement, which makes the snapshot less authoritative. If JSON strings are required, encode invalid UTF-8 explicitly instead of pretending it was text.\\n\\n[P2] Bad GitButler metadata drops all branch/commit observations instead of falling back.  \\n[environment.rs:220](/Users/kiril/src/gitbutler/crates/but-agentlog/src/environment.rs:220) chooses the metadata path based on `virtual_branches.toml` existence, and [environment.rs:223](/Users/kiril/src/gitbutler/crates/but-agentlog/src/environment.rs:223) returns an error if that file cannot be read. That turns the whole workspace snapshot into `workspace_unavailable`, even though the same repo could still produce plain Git branch/commit facts through `EmptyRefMetadata` at [environment.rs:227](/Users/kiril/src/gitbutler/crates/but-agentlog/src/environment.rs:227). For best-effort capture, stale/corrupt sidecar metadata should probably degrade stack/review richness, not erase plain branch evidence.\\n\\nI ran the focused Environment tests while reviewing: `cargo test -p but-agentlog capture_turn_stores --quiet` passed. No files edited.\"}}\n</subagent_notification>","tool_name":null,"tool_input":null,"source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-05-20T15:19:04.456Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"message","role":"user"}}}